---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Admonition from "../components/Admonition.astro";

const meta = {
  title: "About — Journal Foundation",
  description:
    "Self-host practical things—chat, private files, photos, and AI—then learn the open protocols (Cipherlot & Journal Vault) that make it possible.",
  url: "https://journalfoundation.org/about",
  image: "/images/journal_network_background.png",
};
---

<BaseLayout title={meta.title} description={meta.description}>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <meta property="og:title" content={meta.title} />
    <meta property="og:description" content={meta.description} />
    <meta property="og:image" content={meta.image} />
    <meta property="og:type" content="website" />
    <meta property="og:url" content={meta.url} />
    <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image" />
    <link rel="canonical" href={meta.url} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <h1>Custody first. AI without surrender.</h1>
    <p class="subhead">
      Use powerful digital tools—including AI—<strong>without</strong> handing your life to a platform.
    </p>
    <div class="cta">
      <a class="btn primary" href="/docs/10-how-to/run-a-vault-locally">Self-host your chat</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/docs/10-how-to/run-a-vault-locally">Share privately</a>
      <a class="link" href="/cypherlots">Learn the protocols</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What you can do today (in minutes)</h2>
    <p>Four simple ways to get value—without becoming “a node operator.”</p>
    <div class="cards">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Self-host your chat (history you actually own)</h3>
        <p>Keep conversations, system messages, and context on your own device. Add new clients any time.</p>
        <a class="btn small" href="/docs/10-how-to/run-a-vault-locally">Self-host your chat</a>
        <a class="link small" href="/docs/10-how-to/connect-a-client">Connect a client →</a>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Share a private recipe (or an hour-long how-to video)</h3>
        <p>Send the chili recipe—or a 60-minute walkthrough—to one cousin, not the whole internet. Revocable, auditable access.</p>
        <a class="btn small" href="/docs/10-how-to/run-a-vault-locally">Share a private recipe</a>
        <!-- Future guide: /docs/10-how-to/share-a-private-file.mdx -->
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Share beach photos with Grandma—only Grandma</h3>
        <p>No feeds, no trackers, no ads. Just your photos, encrypted, delivered to the one person you choose.</p>
        <a class="btn small" href="/docs/10-how-to/run-a-vault-locally">Share photos privately</a>
        <!-- Future guide: /docs/10-how-to/share-photos-privately.mdx -->
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Private AI with your own data and persona</h3>
        <p>Use AI on your terms: chat history and persona prompts live in your Vault; tools get capability-scoped, time-bound access.</p>
        <a class="btn small" href="/docs/20-explanations/threat-model-overview">Run private AI with your data</a>
        <!-- Future guide: /docs/20-explanations/ai-with-your-vault.mdx -->
      </article>
    </div>
    <p class="note">
      (All of the above are encrypted at rest and in transit. Access is <strong>capability-based</strong> and <strong>revocable</strong>.)
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Under the hood (protocols, not platforms)</h2>
    <p>
      Platforms come and go. Protocols persist. Journal Foundation publishes open specifications and reference tools so anyone can
      <strong>own their data</strong>, <strong>grant precise access</strong>, and enjoy rich AI experiences—without lock-in.
    </p>
    <h3>Cipherlot — your personal, encrypted data node</h3>
    <p>
      Think “safe-deposit box you control” with precise, revocable capabilities for people, apps, and AI agents. Designed for
      <strong>easy self-hosting</strong> (no static IP required).
    </p>
    <h3>Journal Vault — encryption-first, graph-aware store</h3>
    <p>
      Holds large files <strong>and</strong> graph-structured knowledge for modern retrieval/AI. Built with <strong>segments</strong> so different agents can access only what
      they’re allowed—no more.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a class="link" href="/cypherlots">Learn the protocols →</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Threat model &amp; tradeoffs</h2>
    <Admonition kind="warning" title="Honest by design">
      <p><strong>Default defense:</strong> advertisers, data brokers, corporate profiling, and political targeting.</p>
      <p><strong>We optimize for:</strong> real-world usability and low-friction self-hosting.</p>
      <p>
        <strong>We do not claim by default:</strong> resistance to a <em>global passive adversary</em> (e.g., nation-state monitoring). Advanced hardening paths are compatible with
        the spec and will be documented.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Honest security beats perfect security nobody deploys.</em>
        <a href="/docs/20-explanations/threat-model-overview"> Read the threat model →</a>
      </p>
    </Admonition>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why we exist</h2>
    <p>Humans are influenceable. That isn’t good or bad—it’s human.</p>
    <p>
      Fire warms homes when it stays in a <em>ring</em>. Knives serve us when they live in a <em>sheath</em>. The internet and big data are tools of the same kind: powerful,
      helpful, and—without guardrails—easily misused.
    </p>
    <p>
      When personal data sits in the open, <strong>influence pools like water under gravity</strong>—flowing toward those positioned to shape what we see, buy, and believe. We’re
      not here to fear technology. We’re here to <strong>use it safely</strong>: keep the fire in the ring, the knife in the sheath, and <strong>personal data in our custody</strong>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Respect for adjacent work</h2>
    <p>
      We applaud Solid Pods, AT Protocol/Bluesky, Mastodon, Signal/Session, and others. They solve important problems. Our focus is a different prerequisite:
      <strong>complete personal custody</strong> of arbitrarily large, graph-addressable data—encryption-first, capability-scoped, easy to self-host, and designed for AI workflows—
      <strong>without</strong> tokenomics or global sharding.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Founder’s note</h2>
    <p>
      I’m <strong>John Benac</strong>. I want modern intelligence—and I refuse the bargain where my data becomes the product. When I couldn’t find a protocol stack that kept data
      close, safe, and truly useful for AI, I followed a familiar open-source pattern. Inspired by <strong>Linux</strong>, <strong>Git</strong>, and <strong>Wikipedia</strong>, Journal Foundation is building
      <strong>Cipherlot</strong> and <strong>Journal Vault</strong> as simple, durable primitives—so the ecosystem that grows on top can be open, private, and human-serving.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Transparency &amp; governance</h2>
    <p>
      Funding, expenditures, roadmaps, and decisions are public.
      <a href="/governance"> See governance &amp; transparency →</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>FAQ (short)</h2>
    <details>
      <summary>Do I need a static IP or to “support a network”?</summary>
      <p>No. Cipherlot favors low-friction self-hosting. You’re not “running infrastructure for others”—you’re running <em>yours</em>.</p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Where does AI run?</summary>
      <p>Use the provider you trust (local or cloud). Your Vault controls exactly what they can see and for how long.</p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>What about metadata?</summary>
      <p>We minimize what’s needed to function. For stronger protections against global adversaries, follow our hardening guide.</p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How is this different from federation or blockchain?</summary>
      <p>Different missions. We avoid tokenomics and global sharding to keep custody complete and dependencies minimal.</p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Can I share big files?</summary>
      <p>Yes—Vaults support large media and graph-structured knowledge with capability-scoped, revocable access.</p>
    </details>
  </section>

  <style>
    section {
      max-width: 74ch;
      margin: 0 auto 2.5rem;
    }

    .hero {
      max-width: 72ch;
      margin: 4rem auto 2rem;
    }

    .subhead {
      font-size: 1.125rem;
      color: var(--text-muted);
      margin-top: 0.75rem;
    }

    .cta {
      display: flex;
      gap: 0.75rem;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      margin: 1rem 0 2rem;
    }

    .btn {
      padding: 0.7rem 1rem;
      border-radius: 8px;
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      text-decoration: none;
      color: inherit;
    }

    .btn.primary {
      background: var(--accent);
      color: #fff;
      border-color: var(--accent);
    }

    .btn.small {
      padding: 0.55rem 0.85rem;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
    }

    .link {
      text-decoration: underline;
    }

    .link.small {
      display: inline-block;
      margin-top: 0.35rem;
    }

    .cards {
      display: grid;
      gap: 1rem;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(240px, 1fr));
      margin: 1rem 0;
    }

    .card {
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: 12px;
      padding: 1rem;
      background: var(--card-bg, #fff);
    }

    .note {
      color: var(--text-muted);
      margin-top: 0.5rem;
    }

    details {
      border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
      padding: 0.75rem 0;
    }

    details:first-of-type {
      border-top: 0;
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
